{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774460285,"nonce":"V0AihalMgCop+kTbzK9iSVS4i2c=","message":"**Population-based adversary approach**\n\nContext: addresses loss oscillation and weak SISU conditioning observed in single-adversary minimax training.\n\n**Literature references:**\n- Vinitsky et al. (2020) — population-based adversarial training for robust RL. Maintains a pool of K adversaries; each iteration randomly assigns one to each training episode. Prevents controller from overfitting to a single adversary strategy.\n- AlphaStar (Vinyals et al. 2019) — league training with diverse opponents. Similar principle: robustness emerges from exposure to a distribution of adversaries rather than co-adaptation with one.\n\n**Implementation plan:**\n- K=5 adversaries (each a GaussianBumpAdversary with n_bumps=3, so 15 params per adversary = 75 total params)\n- Random permutation per iteration: each batch element gets a randomly selected adversary from the pool\n- All K adversaries updated on their respective inner-loop steps; controller updated on the outer step against the full mixture\n- Prevents the oscillation cycle where controller and single adversary chase each other\n\n**Extension — SISU-stratified assignment:**\n- Assign adversaries to SISU bins (e.g., adversary k specializes in SISU range [k/K, (k+1)/K])\n- This naturally discovers SISU-dependent worst-case perturbation profiles\n- Can analyze post-training which SISU levels are hardest to make robust\n\nThis addresses the loss oscillation problem (diversified adversary pool breaks co-adaptation) and should produce stronger SISU conditioning (adversaries that specialize per-SISU-level).","files":null}]}